name: NSD: Name Server Daemon
description:
The NLnet Labs Name Server Daemon (NSD) is an authoritative RFC compliant DNS nameserver. It was ﬁrst conceived to allow for more genetic diversity for DNS server implementations used by the root-server system and it has been developed for operations in environments where speed, reliability, stability, and security are of high importance. NSD is currently used by a number of root servers operators, by top-level domain registries, ISPs, CDNs, and individuals.

NLnet Labs is committed to support NSD and its other software products on a best effort basis, free of charge. This form of community support is offered through a mailing lists and the ’bugzilla’ web interface. If for any reason NLnet Labs would stop community support of NSD such would be announced on our web pages at least two years in advance.
interact_justification: On the project page one can find links to mailing list, bugzilla, etc. See https://www.nlnetlabs.nl/projects/nsd/
contribution_justification:
We use NSD mailing list for interaction with users and accept patches via emails. We also have a GitHub repository for users to send pull requests.
- https://www.nlnetlabs.nl/projects/nsd/
- https://github.com/NLnetLabs/nsd
contribution_requirements_justification: We accept contributions, but will review *all* code that will be included in the NSD trunk. Sometimes the code is written in the same style and with the same quality we require, and will be accepted straight away. Sometimes we review the code and improve or rewrite some parts before the code is merged in the repository.
license_location_justification:
Source and header files refer to:

/*
 *  See LICENSE for the license.
 */
 
https://github.com/NLnetLabs/nsd/blob/master/LICENSE
floss_license_justification: We use for all our software BSD 3-clause license. The BSD-3-Clause license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The BSD-3-Clause license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: https://www.nlnetlabs.nl/projects/nsd/documentation.html
documentation_interface_justification:
Documentation web page and man pages:
- https://www.nlnetlabs.nl/projects/nsd/documentation.html
- https://www.nlnetlabs.nl/projects/nsd/nsd.8.html
- https://www.nlnetlabs.nl/projects/nsd/nsd-control.8.html
- (see project web page https://www.nlnetlabs.nl/projects/nsd/)
repo_public_justification:
https://www.nlnetlabs.nl/svn/nsd/
https://github.com/NLnetLabs/nsd
repo_track_justification: SVN repository show history.
repo_interim_justification: Interim versions are visible in SVN trunk (during development, and in history).
repo_distributed_justification: https://github.com/NLnetLabs/nsd
version_tags_justification: Available in the branches in SVN repository.
enhancement_responses_justification: We are actively involving the community to develop and improve NSD.
test_justification: Test system is part of the software distribution.
know_secure_design_justification: NLnet Labs has at least two primary developers involved in NSD.
crypto_call_justification: We are very strict *not* to implement our own cryptographic functions and use well-know and well-established libraries.
crypto_keylength_justification: The software does support different key lengths, but user needs to specify/determine the key length needed/required.
crypto_pfs_justification: Not relevant for an authoritative name server.
delivery_mitm_justification: Answered with "Met", but actually not relevant for an authoritative name server.  For DNSSEC the data (RR sets) are signed and can be validated on authenticity.
dynamic_analysis_justification: NSD has been tested with fuzzing tools by external party.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: See comment above, and valgrind is used for debugging and profiling
discussion_justification:
We have bugzilla for our software products, including NSD.  
https://www.nlnetlabs.nl/bugs-script/buglist.cgi?bug_status=NEW&bug_status=ASSIGNED&bug_status=REOPENED&cmdtype=doit&product=nsd

We have not enable issues tracking in GitHub.

Bug reports are accepted via bugzilla

Comments about code on the NSD mailing list.

name: TensorFlow
description: Computation using data flow graphs for scalable machine learning
description_good_justification: On the tensorflow.org home page, in the "About TensorFlow" box.
interact_justification:
Contributions howto is in the canonical place: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
How to obtain: installation guides are here: https://www.tensorflow.org/install/, including how to install from source
How to provide feedback: community site, "Support" section (on the bottom): https://www.tensorflow.org/community/welcome
contribution_justification: Contributions howto is in the canonical place: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
contribution_requirements_justification: Contributions howto: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md includes sections on Python/C++ style used, review standards and process.
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification:
TensorFlow documentation, including most of tensorflow.org is built using custom tooling from sources in the repository itself (https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/tree/master/tensorflow/docs_src as well as inline docs in the source code). In particular:

API reference documentation:
https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/

Getting started:
https://www.tensorflow.org/get_started/

Tutorials:
https://www.tensorflow.org/tutorials/

Programmer's guide
https://www.tensorflow.org/programmers_guide/
documentation_interface_justification:
There is the API reference: 
https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/

Also, guides on how to integrate TensorFlow models (maybe, the output?) into downstream software: 
https://www.tensorflow.org/deploy/
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: The code repository includes all intermediate commits in the repo, as well as tags for alpha versions and release candidates where those exists.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_unique_justification: We use semver 2.0, as explained here: https://www.tensorflow.org/programmers_guide/version_compat
release_notes_justification: Please see https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/releases for the public release notes by release, we also maintain this as a single file: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/RELEASE.md.
release_notes_vulns_justification: We have started to release CVEs for vulnerabilities reported through our reporting process, and will identify fixes for those in release notes.
report_responses_justification: You could collect statistics from https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues, but we try to reply to every issue.
enhancement_responses_justification: We try to respond to all feature requests.
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/SECURITY.md has an explanation of best security practices, along with a process for reporting vulnerabilities.
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/SECURITY.md includes a PGP key that can be used for privately reporting issues to security@tensorflow.org
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/SECURITY.md explains a commitment to initial response within a business day, instituted Feb 2018. Within the last 6 months, we have responded to vulnerability reports within 14 days.
build_justification: TensorFlow uses bazel, but supports building interesting parts with either CMAKE or via Makefiles.
build_common_tools_justification: bazel, cmake and make should count as common tools.
build_floss_tools_justification: Only OSS tooling is required to build TensorFlow, although some features (OpenCL support, CUDA support) require proprietary compilers.
test_justification: Tests are maintained with TensorFlow, in files next to the code.
test_invocation_justification: The tests are invocable in the standard way for the build system (bazel or cmake). Since TensorFlow is written in at least two languages (not counting the language bindings), language level testing doesn't make as much sense.
test_most_justification: Code Coverage is above 90% for non-contrib TensorFlow.
test_policy_justification: All new code submitted to TensorFlow is supposed to have tests, enforced by human review (see https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines-and-philosophy-for-contribution)
tests_are_added_justification: PRs are rejected or stalled for lack of tests. You can look through the PRs we accept and see that there are tests, and that tests are asked for if not present.
tests_documented_added_justification:
Our contributions guidelines state that "Include unit tests when you contribute new features, as they help to a) prove that your code works correctly, b) guard against future breaking changes to lower the maintenance cost. Bug fixes also generally require unit tests, because the presence of bugs usually indicates insufficient test coverage."

(https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines-and-philosophy-for-contribution)
warnings_fixed_justification: Because we compile the C++ parts of TF for many different platforms (and with many different compilers), it is not possible to fix all warnings, but we do try to fix warnings where we can (and we accept contributions doing nothing but fix compiler warnings on some platforms).
warnings_strict_justification: There are likely optional warnings we could enable but don't.
know_secure_design_justification: There are several people with relevant experience on the TensorFlow team.
know_common_errors_justification: There are several people with relevant experience on the TensorFlow team.
delivery_mitm_justification: Binary downloads are available through https. Packages are not signed, but checksums are published on GitHub.
delivery_unsigned_justification: We do not use any such mechanism in TensorFlow, or for the delivery of TensorFlow.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: No publicly known medium or high severity vulnerabilities at the moment. Vulnerabilities that have become known were fixed (e.g. https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/14967, within a day of the initial report).
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: So far, no critical vulnerabilities reported.
static_analysis_justification:
We're using Clangs analysis tools: 
http://clang.llvm.org/docs/AddressSanitizer.html
http://clang.llvm.org/docs/ThreadSanitizer.html
http://clang.llvm.org/docs/MemorySanitizer.html

as well as cpplint and clang-tidy for C++ code, and pylint for Python.
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: All our analysis tools are general purpose. However, AddressSanitizer does have "rules to look for common vulnerabilities in the analyzed language" (buffer overruns in particular).
static_analysis_fixed_justification: Static analysis is run continuously, and issues found are treated like broken builds and fixed as soon as feasible.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: We do not use a fuzzer, but we do use ASAN, MSAN, and TSAN (see static analysis above).
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: PRs are tested before merge, and CI runs on every commit to master.
discussion_justification:
GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
Also, open and archived mailing list: discuss@tensorflow.org
no_leaked_credentials_justification: No private credentials in the repositories.
english_justification: See our documentation and track record of accepting bug reports in the issue tracker, mostly in English.
hardened_site_justification: // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff". // One or more of the required security hardening headers is missing.
installation_common_justification: We publish pip packages to pypi.
governance_justification: TensorFlow is governed by the TensorFlow team, but this is not clearly and publicly documented.
roles_responsibilities_justification: See governance above. No public documentation of roles.
access_continuity_justification: There is a backup person with credentials and working knowledge for all critical infrastructure. Not sure what URL to provide here -- the github teams page cannot be accessed by non-members, and internal Google pages cannot be seen either.
bus_factor_justification: Truck-Factor helpfully has the information for tensorflow on the site. https://github.com/aserg-ufmg/Truck-Factor
documentation_roadmap_justification: We have a roadmap (https://www.tensorflow.org/about/roadmap), but it's too infrequently updated to count.
documentation_architecture_justification: I addition to the documentation, we have published several papers on the architecture: https://www.tensorflow.org/about/bib.
documentation_security_justification: We need to provide a security page (see also reporting above).
documentation_quick_start_justification: We have a getting started section here: https://www.tensorflow.org/get_started/get_started
documentation_current_justification: We accept issues and PRs for documentation fixes and treat them the same as reports of defects to the software itself.
documentation_achievements_justification: We haven't actively worked to achieve any badges etc., but if we did, we would also post the result (including this badge). These would likely appear on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: TensorFlow is mostly exposed as an API, with reduced accessibility concerns. However, we have tried to make sure that our website follows accessibility standards, and that UI components (TensorBoard) are accessible.
internationalization_justification: TensorFlow itself does not deal with text directly.
maintenance_or_update_justification: Where the upgrade is hard (0.12 -> 1.0) we have provided scripts to help users migrate, and we plan to do the same in the future.
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio: We have no documented reporting process in place.
build_standard_variables_justification: Bazel builds are hermetic (and must be for distributed builds), and DO NOT respect environment variables unless those are explicitly declared to the build system (with --action_env=... or in the bazel.rc).
build_preserve_debug_justification: You can make a debug build, and if you do, the generated pip package will come with debugging symbols.
build_non_recursive_justification: bazel does not automatically recurse into subdirectories.
build_repeatable_justification: bazel builds are hermetic and repeatable.
installation_standard_variables_justific: Installation via pip uses Python's site-packages directories.
installation_development_quick_justifica: We provide docker containers equivalent to our CI setup.
external_dependencies_justification: See the explicit dependency declaration in our bazel workspace: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/workspace.bzl
dependency_monitoring_justification: We have no process to regularly screen our dependencies.
updateable_reused_components_justificati: We pin components to explicit versions. Updating requires rebuilding.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: Automated tests are run on every commit to master.
regression_tests_added50_justification: Every bugfix should come with a test as described in our contributions policy: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#general-guidelines-and-philosophy-for-contribution
